<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1436,1500,2029]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,323,1753,1778]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Song, 1993" authorityName="Song" authorityYear="1993" box="[333,765,1753,1777]" class="Insecta" family="Crambidae" genus="Glaucocharis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longqiensis">
<emphasis box="[333,623,1753,1777]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Glaucocharis longqiensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Song" box="[634,765,1753,1777]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" refString="Song, S. M. (1993) Lepidoptera: Pyralidae and Zygaenidae. In: Huang, C. M. (ed.), Animals of Longqi Mountain. China Forestry Publishing House, Beijing. 414 - 473 pp." type="book chapter" year="1993">
Song, 
<number box="[709,765,1753,1777]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="1993.0">1993</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<emphasis box="[925,1071,1753,1777]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">G. m e l i s t o m a</emphasis>
(Meyrick, 
<number box="[1207,1264,1753,1777]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="1931.0">1931</number>
) in the female genitalia, but can be distinguished by the absence of the lamella vaginalis and the absence of the protuberance of the ductus bursae. In 
<emphasis box="[395,538,1825,1849]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">G. m e l i s t o m a</emphasis>
, the lamellae vaginalis is present and the posterior part of the ductus bursae is protuberant to one side. The male genitalia of the two species are conspicuously different: the valva points outward distally and bears an apical spine in 
<taxonomicName box="[551,709,1897,1921]" class="Insecta" family="Crambidae" genus="Glaucocharis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longqiensis">
<emphasis box="[551,709,1897,1921]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">G. longqiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; while the valva points inward distally, and lacks the apical spine in 
<emphasis box="[180,321,1933,1957]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">G. m e l i s t o m a</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="22" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1436,1500,2029]" box="[201,751,1969,1994]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,346,1969,1994]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Description.</emphasis>
Adult forewing length 
<quantity box="[609,748,1969,1993]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" metricValueMax="5.5" metricValueMin="4.5" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" unit="mm" value="5.0" valueMax="5.5" valueMin="4.5">4.5–5.5 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1436,1500,2029]" lastBlockId="21.[151,1437,151,356]" lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="22" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
Female genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[405,491,2005,2029]" captionStart="FIGURES 30 – 33" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1932,1955]" captionTargetBox="[220,1378,845,1881]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[188,1398,815,1911]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 30 – 33. Female genitalia of Glaucocharis spp. 30. G. hastatella Song &amp; Chen, genitalia slide No. LWC 08258; 31. G. omeishani (Bleszynski), genitalia slide No. LWC 08256; 32. G. longqiensis Song, genitalia slide No. LWC 07203; 33. G. parmulella Wang &amp; Sung, genitalia slide No. LWC 07209 (scales: 0.5 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/213867/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
Fig. 
<number box="[459,491,2005,2029]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="32.0">32</number>
</figureCitation>
). Papilla analis ovate, about one third length of apophysis posterioris. Tergite eight about half as long as apophysis anterioris. Ostium bursae about twice as wide as median part of ductus bursae. Ductus bursae curved slightly. Ductus seminalis arising from anterior one fourth of ductus bursae. Corpus bursae ovate; signum rounded, placed at posterior one third of corpus bursae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,151,356]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,354,259,284]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[361,428,260,284]" name="China" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">China</collectingCountry>
(Fujian, Guangxi, Guizhou, Hainan, Jiangxi, Sichuan, Yunnan). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,317,296,320]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Remarks.</emphasis>
The female of this species is described for the first time. 
<bibRefCitation author="Song" box="[993,1134,295,319]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" refString="Song, S. M. (1993) Lepidoptera: Pyralidae and Zygaenidae. In: Huang, C. M. (ed.), Animals of Longqi Mountain. China Forestry Publishing House, Beijing. 414 - 473 pp." type="book chapter" year="1993">
Song (
<number box="[1068,1126,295,319]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="1993.0">1993</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
described and figured the male adlut and genitalia.
</paragraph>
